<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="127" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,151,738]" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,151,177]" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Lateral surface of carapace smooth (except for supraorbital spines). Carapace with 1 supraorbital spine on each side; pterygostomial spine well developed, sharp; without branchiostegal spine; antennal spine present. Mandibular palp with 2 articles. Maxilliped 3 without exopod. Pereopod 2 carpus with 7 articles. Pereopods 3–5 meri with lateral spines. Pereopods without arthrobranchs. Abdominal segments dorsally rounded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="127" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,151,738]" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,319,338,364]" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="White" authorityYear="1847" box="[326,424,338,363]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lebbeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[326,424,338,363]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">Lebbeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
contains 47 described species with the species known up until 2004 listed by Komai 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">et al.</emphasis>
(2004). Three species were described later by 
<bibRefCitation author="Jensen, G. C." box="[745,916,376,402]" pageId="1" pageNumber="127" pagination="23 - 43" refId="ref5944" refString="Jensen, G. C. (2006) Three new species of Lebbeus (Crustacea: Decapoda: Hippolytidae) from the northeastern Pacific. Zootaxa, 1383, 23 - 43." type="journal article" year="2006">Jensen (2006)</bibRefCitation>
. The genus has a cosmopolitan distribution extending from cold to tropical waters, including the Antarctic and the Arctic, although the species generally have a narrow geographic range (Komai 
<emphasis box="[636,695,450,475]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">et al.</emphasis>
2004). Few species have been described from South America, Africa or 
<collectingCountry box="[268,381,488,514]" name="Australia" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">Australia</collectingCountry>
. Approximately half of the described species are from the north-western Pacific (waters off 
<collectingCountry box="[194,265,525,551]" name="Japan" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">Japan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[277,360,525,551]" name="Russia" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">Russia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[373,445,525,551]" name="South Korea" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">Korea</collectingCountry>
and northern 
<collectingCountry box="[615,688,525,551]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">China</collectingCountry>
) and a key to these species was published by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hayashi, K. - I." box="[1243,1432,525,551]" pageId="1" pageNumber="127" pagination="107 - 138" refId="ref5820" refString="Hayashi, K. - I. (1992) Studies on the hippolytid shrimps from Japan: VIII. The genus Lebbeus White. Journal of Shimonoseki University of Fisheries, 40, 107 - 138." type="journal article" year="1992">Hayashi (1992)</bibRefCitation>
. Variation in the development of epipods on pereopods 1−3 has commonly been used to diagnose and group species (
<bibRefCitation author="Fransen, C. H. J. M." box="[255,425,600,626]" pageId="1" pageNumber="127" pagination="231 - 260" refId="ref5688" refString="Fransen, C. H. J. M. (1997) Lebbeus africanus spec. nov., a new shrimp (Crustacea, Decapoda, Caridea, Hippolytidae) from Mauritian waters, with descriptions of four other species in the genus. Zoologische Mededelingen, Leiden, 71, 231 - 260." type="journal article" year="1997">Fransen 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hayashi, K. - I." box="[438,609,600,626]" pageId="1" pageNumber="127" pagination="107 - 138" refId="ref5820" refString="Hayashi, K. - I. (1992) Studies on the hippolytid shrimps from Japan: VIII. The genus Lebbeus White. Journal of Shimonoseki University of Fisheries, 40, 107 - 138." type="journal article" year="1992">Hayashi 1992</bibRefCitation>
; Komai 
<emphasis box="[712,774,600,625]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">et al.</emphasis>
2004) but intraspecific variation in the presence of an epipod on pereopod 3 has been reported (Komai 
<emphasis box="[729,788,637,662]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">et al.</emphasis>
2004). The new species fall into a small group of only four species distinguished by possession of a high crest on the carapace and epipods on the first two pereopods.
</paragraph>
